The CompTIA Project+ certification validates your expertise and opens doors to higher-paying roles in IT and cybersecurity. Whether you are just starting your study journey or doing a final review, this guide breaks down everything you need to know to pass the PK0-005 exam.

## Exam Overview

- **Certification:** CompTIA Project+
- **Exam Code:** PK0-005
- **Vendor:** CompTIA
- **Cost:** $358 USD
- **Duration:** 90 minutes
- **Questions:** Up to 95 questions
- **Passing Score:** 710 out of 900
- **Format:** Multiple choice + Performance-based questions (PBQs)
- **Prerequisites:** None required (12 months project management experience recommended)

## Domain Breakdown

Understanding the exam domains and their weights is critical for efficient study planning. Focus more time on heavily-weighted domains while ensuring you cover all areas.

### Domain 1: Project Management Concepts (33%)

- 1.1 Summarize the properties of a project
- 1.2 Classify project roles and responsibilities
- 1.3 Compare and contrast standard project phases
- 1.4 Identify the basics of project cost control
- 1.5 Identify common project team organizational structures

**Key concepts:** Project vs Operations, Triple Constraint (Scope, Time, Cost), Project Stakeholders and Roles, Project Sponsor vs Project Manager, PMO (Project Management Office), Project Charter, Organizational Structures (Functional, Matrix, Projectized), Feasibility Analysis

### Domain 2: Project Life Cycle Phases (30%)

- 2.1 Explain activities and deliverables within the initiation phase
- 2.2 Explain activities and deliverables within the planning phase
- 2.3 Explain activities and deliverables within the execution phase
- 2.4 Explain activities and deliverables within the monitoring and controlling phase
- 2.5 Explain activities and deliverables within the closing phase

**Key concepts:** Project Initiation Document (PID), Work Breakdown Structure (WBS), Gantt Charts and Network Diagrams, Critical Path Method (CPM), PERT Estimation, Resource Allocation and Leveling, Risk Register and Risk Response Strategies, Quality Assurance vs Quality Control

### Domain 3: Communication and Change Management (15%)

- 3.1 Given a scenario, use communication methods and tools
- 3.2 Explain the importance of the change management process
- 3.3 Explain the purpose of a stakeholder register

**Key concepts:** Communication Plan, Stakeholder Analysis and Register, RACI Matrix (Responsible, Accountable, Consulted, Informed), Change Control Board (CCB), Change Request Process, Status Reports and Dashboards, Escalation Procedures, Conflict Resolution Techniques

### Domain 4: Tools and Documentation (12%)

- 4.1 Compare and contrast project management tools
- 4.2 Given a scenario, use project management documentation
- 4.3 Identify common project management artifacts

**Key concepts:** Project Scheduling Software (MS Project, Jira), Kanban Boards and Task Trackers, Project Plan vs Project Schedule, Scope Statement and SOW, Requirements Traceability Matrix, Issue Log and Action Items, Risk Register, Budget Tracking Documents

### Domain 5: Basics of Agile (10%)

- 5.1 Summarize the core values and principles of Agile
- 5.2 Compare and contrast Agile frameworks
- 5.3 Explain common Agile roles, artifacts, and ceremonies

**Key concepts:** Agile Manifesto (4 Values, 12 Principles), Scrum Framework (Sprints, Backlog, Ceremonies), Kanban Methodology, Product Owner vs Scrum Master, User Stories and Story Points, Sprint Planning and Retrospectives, Daily Standups, Velocity and Burndown Charts


## Recommended Study Timeline

Plan for approximately **6-10 weeks** of dedicated study. Here is a suggested weekly breakdown:

- **Week 1:** Domain 1: PM Concepts — Project properties, Triple constraint, Stakeholders, Organizational structures
- **Week 2:** Domain 1: PM Foundations — Project charter, Feasibility analysis, Business case, Project selection
- **Week 3:** Domain 2: Initiation & Planning — PID, WBS, Gantt charts, CPM, PERT, Resource planning
- **Week 4:** Domain 2: Execution & Control — Risk management, EVM, Quality assurance, Monitoring techniques
- **Week 5:** Domain 2: Closing — Lessons learned, Final deliverables, Project sign-off, Archiving
- **Week 6:** Domain 3: Communication — Communication plans, RACI, Stakeholder register, Conflict resolution
- **Week 7:** Domain 3: Change Management — Change control board, Change requests, Escalation, Impact analysis
- **Week 8:** Full Review: Practice tests, EVM calculations, PBQ practice, Exam logistics

## Top Study Tips

1. **Start with the official exam objectives.** Download them from the CompTIA website and use them as your study checklist. Every exam question maps to a specific objective.

2. **Use active recall over passive reading.** Instead of re-reading notes, test yourself with practice questions after each study session. This dramatically improves retention.

3. **Focus on heavily-weighted domains first.** Domains with higher percentages appear more on the exam. Master these before moving to lower-weighted areas.

4. **Build hands-on experience.** Set up a lab environment and practice the skills you are studying. Hands-on experience is especially valuable for performance-based questions.

5. **Take practice exams under real conditions.** Time yourself, eliminate distractions, and simulate the exam environment. Review every wrong answer and understand why it was wrong.

